.TH "runit\-init" "8" 
.SH NAME
init \- a UNIX process no 1
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]init\f[R] [ 0 | 6 ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]runit\-init\f[R] is the first process the kernel starts.
If \f[B]runit\-init\f[R] is started as process no 1, it runs and
replaces itself with \f[B]runit\f[R](8).
.PP
If \f[B]runit\-init\f[R] is started while the system is up, it must be
either called as \f[B]init 0\f[R] or \f[B]init 6\f[R]:
.TP
\f[B]init 0\f[R]
tells the Unix process no 1 to shutdown and halt the system.
To signal \f[B]runit\f[R](8) the system halt request,
\f[B]runit\-init\f[R] removes all permissions of the file
\f[I]/etc/runit/reboot\f[R] (chmod 0), and sets the execute by owner
permission of the file \f[I]/etc/runit/stopit\f[R] (chmod 100).
Then a CONT signal is sent to \f[B]runit\f[R](8).
.TP
\f[B]init 6\f[R]
tells the Unix process no 1 to shutdown and reboot the system.
To signal \f[B]runit\f[R](8) the system reboot request,
\f[B]runit\-init\f[R] sets the execute by owner permission of the files
\f[I]/etc/runit/reboot\f[R] and \f[I]/etc/runit/stopit\f[R] (chmod 100).
Then a CONT signal is sent to \f[B]runit\f[R](8).
.SH EXIT CODES
\f[B]runit\-init\f[R] returns 111 on error, 0 in all other cases.
